  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent, detect, and report money laundering activities. Key requirements typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Performing background checks\n- Monitoring suspicious transactions\n- Maintaining detailed customer records\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Informing regulatory authorities about potential money laundering\n\n3. Know Your Customer (KYC) Regulations\n- Establishing customer risk profiles\n- Conducting ongoing monitoring\n- Implementing risk-based compliance procedures\n\n4. Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Compliance Programs\n- Developing internal policies\n- Training employees\n- Implementing transaction monitoring systems\n- Conducting regular risk assessments\n\n5. Legal Consequences\n- Potential significant financial penalties\n- Possible criminal charges\n- Potential loss of banking licenses\n\nThese obligations are typically enforced by regulations like the Bank Secrecy Act in the United States and similar laws in other countries, designed to prevent financial crimes and terrorist financing.",
